Exam-prep tactics.

Start by deciding what to memorise versus what to look up, because the exam does not hand you man pages. Memorise the shape of docker run and its most-used flags, the semantics that separate volumes from bind mounts from in-memory mounts including the seeding-on-empty rule, the rules for when containers can resolve each other by name and how the routing mesh works in swarm, every common dockerfile instruction and its quirks like command versus entry-point and copy versus add, the swarm distinctions between services and tasks and replicated versus global with the rolling-update flags, and the keys of the compose deploy block. Those are the things tested by reflex. By contrast, you can leave to look-up the daemon configuration keys you do not use weekly, the exact profile paths for the mandatory-access-control systems, and the specific cloud-registry hostname schemes, because memorising them burns study time for little return.

The single most important habit is to practise, not just read. Set up a real multi-node swarm, on a few local virtual machines, and make yourself able to do the core operations from memory, initialising and joining a cluster, creating and scaling and updating and rolling back a service, deploying a stack from a file, creating an overlay network, creating and using a secret, and draining and reactivating a node. Reading about these is genuinely not enough, because the exam asks given-this-scenario-what-command and which-of-these-is-true questions, and those reward hands-on fluency.

It pays to study the question style itself. The scenario questions hand you a goal, like update this service two replicas at a time with a delay and automatic rollback on failure, and ask which command does it, and the right answer is the one with the correct update flags. The true-statement questions often have a both-of-these-are-valid option that is easy to overlook. Working through the official sample questions, of which there are about ten published, is high-yield precisely because it tunes you to that phrasing.
